@node Overview "Overview"

    Handy (Amiga OS3.x M68K) V0.95 R1.45 (19/ 1/2013), ported from
    Handy (Windows         ) V0.95       (19/ 2/2007) and
    Handy (Amiga OS4.0 PPC ) V0.80       (22/ 1/2005)

    AmigaOS3.x M68K port by James Jacobs of Amigan Software in 2007-2013.
    AmigaOS4 port by Mathias "AmiDog" Roslund in 2005.
    Original Windows version by Keith Wilkins in 1998-2007.

Handy is an Atari Lynx emulator. It is quite compatible and most ROMs
should work flawlessly.
  The Amiga elements have been backported from OS4.0 to OS3.0, also
replacing the 0.80 emulation core with the 0.95 core and adding features.
The improvements in this version (as compared to the OS4.0 version)
include:

    * based on 0.95 core, not 0.80 core
    * you can play with a joystick
    * you can use an ASL requester to choose which game to play
    * you can run it from Workbench, including support for ToolTypes
    * you can change games without quitting, by pressing F1
    * you can reset the Lynx by pressing F3
    * support for ZIPped games
    * support for loading and saving of LSS2 (snapshot) files
    * no BIOS ROM required
    * source code
    * support for loading and saving of ALR (gameplay recording) files
    * turbo speed on/off toggle
    * autofire on/off toggles
    * stack checking at startup
    * optional 24MHz overclocking

Some of these features (eg. LSS2 saving, ALR support, autofire,
overclocking) are unique to the Amiga version of Handy 0.95.
  AHI sound is available but is turned off by default for speed (SOUND to
turn it on). You need a very fast Amiga for stutter-free sound. Keyboard,
joystick (2-button joysticks are best) and CDł˛ joypad (JOYPAD) are
supported for input.
  The emulator only runs in its own screen. Most features of the Windows
version are not available.
@endnode

@node Requirements "System Requirements"

@{b}Hardware@{ub}             Required        AGA or CyberGraphX
                                     16Mb of RAM
                                     68020+
                     Recommended     68060+
                                     CDł˛ joypad
@{b}Firmware@{ub}             Required        Kickstart 3.0+
@{b}Software@{ub}             Required        OS3.0+
                     Recommended     AHI
                                     cybergraphics.library
                                     OpenURL (for links in this document)

@{b}INCREASE THE STACK@{ub}, approx. 100K (stack 100000 <ENTER>) should be enough.

You will need a very fast Amiga to achieve adequate performance. You can
run it either in a 320-pixel wide AGA screen, or in an 8-bitplane (256
colour) CyberGraphX (or Picasso96 emulating CyberGraphX) screen. There is
optional AHI sound.

Maybe you could run some patches such as BlazeWCP or FBlit to increase the
speed. These have not been tested with Handy but should help performance.
@endnode

@node Usage "Usage"

@{b}INCREASE THE STACK@{ub}, approx. 100K (stack 100000 <ENTER>) should be enough.

@{b}Format:          Handy@{ub}
                 [[FILE=]@{i}romname@{ui}]
                 [REQUESTER]
                 [JOYPAD]
                 [CGFX]
                 [SOUND]
                 [SCREENMODE=@{i}screenmode@{ui}]
                 [NOSTALGIA]
                 [TURBO]
                 [OVERCLOCK]

@{b}Template:@{ub}        FILE/A,REQUESTER/S,JOYPAD/S,CGFX/S,SOUND/S,
                 SCREENMODE/N,NOSTALGIA/S,TURBO/S,OVERCLOCK/S

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}         To emulate the Atari Lynx handheld console.

@{b}Specification:@{ub}

    FILE/S        : filename of the game (in LNX/LSS2 format) you want to
                    play.

    REQUESTER/S   : use screenmode requester (default: CGFX BestModeID/PAL
                    Lores). Note that this has no effect for AGA-only
                    users.

    JOYPAD/S      : CDł˛ joypad (default: joystick). Joypads and joysticks
                    must be in port '2' (the usual "game" port), not port
                    '1' (the usual "mouse" port).

    CGFX/S        : CGFX instead of direct gfxmem access (default: direct
                    gfxmem access).

    SOUND/S       : turn AHI sound on (default: off).

    SCREENMODE/N  : use the specified screenmode (default: CGFX
                    BestModeID/PAL Lores). Note that this has no effect
                    for AGA-only users.

    NOSTALGIA/S   : save the screenshot in Nostalgia:samples/ (default:
                    current directory).

    TURBO/S       : turbo speed on/off (default: off).

    OVERCLOCK/S   : 24MHz master oscillator (instead of 16MHz) (default:
                    16MHz). See below for more details.

    ?             : displays the command line argument format.

The order of the arguments is interchangeable.

You can also use these as ToolTypes.

If you run it from CLI and use the REQUESTER option, the screenmode ID
number (suitable for use as an argument for SCREENMODE) of your chosen
screenmode is displayed afterwards.

The way the screenmode is determined is as follows:

    If CyberGraphX is available,
        If SCREENMODE is specified,
            Use SCREENMODE if suitable, otherwise 320*256*8 AGA PAL mode
        Otherwise, if REQUESTER is specified,
            Use ASL requester to select a screenmode
        Otherwise,
            Choose a suitable CyberGraphX screenmode automagically
    Otherwise,
        Use 320*256*8 AGA PAL mode

Note that the real Atari Lynx takes a second or two to load the game; this
likewise applies to the emulator. If you are unable to run the emulator at
full speed, this delay will obviously be longer. Be patient and the game
will eventually appear :-)

Note that .O, .COM and headerless .LNX files are not supported.

Sometimes changing games (via the F1 key) can crash the emulator. The
cause of this has not yet been determined.

@{b}About LSS (Lynx SnapShot) Files@{ub}

There are two common formats for LSS files: LSS2 and LSS3.
  LSS2 is the superior format; these files contain the relevant game ROM
and thus can be loaded without the need for any LNX file.
  LSS3 files are missing this data.
  This Amiga version can load and save LSS2 files, but cannot load nor
save LSS3 files.
  The Windows version can load but not save LSS2 files, and can load and
save LSS3 files.
  Note that there is a bug which affects both the Windows and Amiga
versions: when loading LSS2 files, the checksum is not calculated
correctly. The implication of this is that if you then save an LSS2
snapshot (or ALR recording), the saved checksum will be incorrect. This
will cause problems when trying to load the LSS2 file into the Windows
version of Handy.

@{b}About ALR (Atari Lynx Recording) Files@{ub}

Support for these is unique to this Amiga port. These are LSS2 files with
a gameplay recording appended. If loaded into other ports of Handy (eg.
Handy for Windows), they are treated as ordinary LSS2 files.
  Loading, resetting, quitting or pressing F7 will stop ALR playback or
recording.
  During recording, the screen border will be red. During playback, the
screen border will be blue.
@endnode

@{b}About Emulator Speed@{ub}

The master oscillator on a standard Lynx I/][ is clocked at approximately
16MHz. There is a popular hardware modification which involves swapping
the 16MHz oscillator for a 24MHz one (ie. overclocking the Lynx), as
described at http://amigan.1emu.net/kolsen/24mhzhack.html, the "Portable
Addiction" e-magazine, and elsewhere. 20/28/32MHz modifications have
also been done by various users but are not currently emulated.
  As all the chips run off this clock, they are all sped up (ie. not only
the CPU) by 50%. On a real Lynx, the sound pitch is also raised; this
is a generally undesirable aspect of the modification and thus is not
emulated.
  The practical use for this is for playing games which are excessively
slow, ie. Hard Drivin', Pinball Jam, Steel Talon, etc. Obviously your
Amiga needs to be able to run Handy at (greater than) full speed for this
to be of any use.
  Turbo mode is effectively the same as overclocking the Lynx to an
infinite number of megahertz. In turbo mode, the emulator is already
running as fast as possible and thus overclocking will make no difference
in that case.

@node Controls "Controls"

Emulator controls (always available):

  Esc                 - Quit
  F1                  - Load ALR/LNX/LSS2
  F3                  - Reset
  F5                  - Save LSS2 snapshot
  F7                  - Start/stop gameplay recording/playback (ALR)
  F9                  - Autofire on/off for button A
  F10                 - Autofire on/off for button B
  Help                - Save screenshot (PCX)
  T                   - Turbo speed on/off
  Y                   - 24mhz clock on/off

Keyboard keys (always available):

  A or D              - Button A
  S                   - Button B
  Q or E              - Button Opt1
  W                   - Button Opt2
  P or ENTER          - Pause
  Arrow keys          - Left, Right, Up, Down

CDł˛ pad buttons (only if JOYPAD is ON):

  Green               - Button Opt1
  Yellow              - Button Opt2
  Red                 - Button A
  Blue                - Button B
  Start               - Pause
  Directional buttons - Left, Right, Up, Down

Joystick controls (only if JOYPAD is OFF):

  Firebutton 1        - Button A
  Firebutton 2        - Button B
  Directional buttons - Left, Right, Up, Down

Esc F1 .. F3 .. F5 .. F7 .. F9 F10
.... . . . . . . . . . . . . . ..   ... Hel   . . . .
..... Q W E . T Y . . . P . . RET             . . . .
... .. A S D . . . . . . . . . UR     Up      . . . .
..... . . . . . . . . . . . .....  Lt Dn Rt   . . . .
   .. .. ................. .. ..              ... . .
@endnode

